reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States on June 23, 2019
reviewDescription: I am beyond disappointed as a loyal user for 25 years and a former employee of Colgate-Palmolive. The Colgate Total SF Whitening paste with "New Formula" tastes like chemicals (AWFUL) during brushing and leaves a chalky feel and a metallic aftertaste. I grew up on Crest and switched to Colgate, when I started working there, because of the great taste and performance of their fantastic toothpaste.  They have completely changed a product that people have loved for decades, probably to achieve cost savings, and my tube ended up in the trash.  Even if Colgate went back to their original formula, it would take a year or so, and they will have done significant damage to the brand image.  I have no confidence that any of their "New Formula" flavors will be any better, so unfortunately I will be switching brands.

reviewDescription: The photo of this product is the reason I chose to purchase this toothpaste. It is the SF type, which has a flavor that we do not like.  When I tried to return the product, Amazon denied my request.  As a customer I feel deceived, and misled into buying a product that I do not want.

reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States on January 18, 2020
reviewDescription: I used Colgate Total advanced whitening toothpaste for the last 15 years. Last year I picked up another 3-pack of it without paying any attention to the new “SF” on the box. As soon as I used the new tube I was disappointed. The flavor was terrible, it slightly burned my tongue, and it did not foam up like the old version. But I kept using it because I figured “what harm can it do?”  Well about midway through the second tube I was looking at a recent picture and realized my teeth were looking pretty brown. Mind you I do NOT smoke or drink tea, coffee, wine, or soda. That’s when I looked on the tube and saw the WARNING that STANNOUS FLUORIDE IS KNOWN TO STAIN TEETH. Why in the world would you make a “whitening” toothpaste using a type of fluoride that is known to cause tooth staining?!? They might THINK that their formula doesn’t stain teeth, but I’ve got a mouth full of currently stained (but previously pearly white) teeth that beg to differ. Since Colgate has gone all in on the stannous (should be called STAINous) fluoride, I’ve had to switch to Crest. I don’t like anything about Crest as much as I liked the OLD Colgate Total Whitening formula, but it beats the heck out of this new junk.BRING BACK THE OLD FORMULA!!!

reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States on May 31, 2019
reviewDescription: My family has been Colgate Total users exclusively for many years. However the recent changes to the "new flavor" has caused our family to switch to another brand. At first I did not realize the awful metallic taste and rawness that lingered in my mouth for hours after brushing was due to the the new formulation, it wasn't until my son asked the same day if I forgot to completely rinse the vinegar out of the coffee maker after cleaning. I did not clean the coffee maker that day.....and hadn't for sometime. Once we compared identical symptoms we realized it was the Colgate Total tooth paste causing unpleasantness and irritation for both of us. When looking at the tube I noticed (in very small lettering) the word "new flavor". I thought "no big deal" I wont use the new formula and just go back to the old. I picked up another box that day that WAS NOT marked on the outer box "new flavor", imagine my surprise when I opened it at home only to have the tube marked "new flavor', very deceptive on the part of Colgate. I have now unwittingly made 2 purchases of "new flavor" that we will not use. At one time Colgate Total was a wonderful product, but that is no longer true....we have switched to AuquaFresh Advanced it tastes good and doesn't leave our mouths sore. Ps. I have noticed since about March of this year there has been nothing but complaints in the reviews of this product. Please listen to your consumers opinions.

reviewTitle: Inferior formula versus all other countries'
reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States 🇺🇸 on December 16, 2019
reviewDescription: Colgate wanted to distance itself from the bad PR tied to the old formula with triclosan and has now turned Colgate Total into what is now essentially Crest Pro Health, which is also based on stannous fluoride.While not a bad product by any means, the formula everywhere else in the world but the United States is made with sodium fluoride, zinc, and arginine.Seemingly, the ADA has cowered Colgate into introducing an inferior formula into the US because many of its dentists sell treatments based on arginine, or Colgate did it preemptively not to incur their wrath. They did the same thing with Colgate Pro-Relief (based on arginine), and Sendodyne Repair & Protect (it is stannous fluoride, while all other countries get the much better formula with Novamin). American consumers get inferior products.Because of this mess, it might be better to get an international version if possible.

reviewTitle: Do not like the new formula
reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States 🇺🇸 on December 8, 2019
reviewDescription: I have been using Colgate Total Whitening gel for many years.  It was one of the first whitening toothpastes to be accepted by the ADA, which is what motivated me to try it.  After trying, I found it was the best toothpaste I had ever used.  It did seem to keep the promise of 12 hours of protection as my teeth felt cleaner at the end of the day than with the other toothpaste I had been using.  With my last trip to the store, I noticed I could no longer find a version that was accepted by the ADA and realized Colgate had quit making the toothpaste I had exclusively bought for ~10 years.  This led me to purchase what I thought was the comparable replacement (this product).  It is, however, not comparable.  The gel is thinner and breaks down more quickly while you are brushing your teeth.  It does not seem to clean my teeth as well nor does it provide the same level of 12 hours of protection.  I imagine there is no review that will impact the company to bring the existing product back, but that is ultimately my hope in writing this review.  I am currently in the process of finding whatever product may be left out there to stockpile what I can.

reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States 🇺🇸 on March 19, 2019
reviewDescription: I ordered the Colgate Total Whitening Toothpaste for myself as other members of my family have sensitivities to the sodium lauryl sulfate in the formula.  I like a nice mint flavor but find that this mint is really intense compared to other mint toothpaste.  It leaves my mouth and tongue feeling burnt by mint and it is not the most pleasing sensation.  It does do a very good job at keeping my mouth feeling fresh for a longer duration which could be due to the intense mint.  My teeth feel clean but I do not feel it does as good of a job at tarter control as I would like.  I do not notice any difference when flossing between this formula and other formulas that do not have tartar control.  I have not noticed outstanding whitening abilities but feel it does a good job at keeping my teeth their normal shade of white.  This is a fairly basic toothpaste with a strong mint flavor.  I am unsure if I would order again because it kind of hurts my mouth.

reviewTitle: Disgusting new flavor, had to switch

reviewDescription: I have used Colgate for almost my whole life. I found the Total paste had the best taste and seemed to do a good job keeping cavities and such at bay. I am extremely sensitive to sucralose in products, it leaves a cloying foul taste in my mouth that only eating can get rid of (kind of defeats the purpose of brushing...) and a lot of companies are not openly declaring that it is in their products. I know with bottled drinks and candies that I have to be careful to check the ingredients, but I did not think I'd have to do this with toothpaste!Even my mother, who isn't as picky with flavors and such, couldn't use it more than once.I have switched to a different Colgate product but am not happy overall with the company's decision to drastically switch the ingredients in my favorite product.

reviewTitle: Not Much Different From Other Colgate & Caused Sores Inside Lips & Mouth
reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States 🇺🇸 on February 1, 2019
reviewDescription: We've been using Colgate toothpaste for years and have tried several of their varieties. According to the label, this one is supposed to be an all-in-one toothpaste. Its a paste versus gel, but it doesn't lather or foam up as much as other Colgate toothpaste. It leaves the mouth and teeth feeling clean and fresh after brushing, but the affects aren't long lasting. The whitening benefits are also very minimal. I don't think its meant to whiten any more than brushing regularly would produce. It definitely doesn't have the same benefits as products designed to only whiten teeth.  As for the sensitivity benefits, I don't think they work as well as Sensodye provides.  As a few other people have mentioned, this toothpaste left the inside of my lips and mouth rather sore.  I didn't make the connection between the toothpaste and the irritation until I read some of the other reviews here. I had noticed that my lips and the inside of my gums felt like I had cold sores and just thought it was caused by the extreme cold or something else, but when I read the reviews I decided to stop using this toothpaste for a few days before writing my review. Within 48 hrs the irritation was gone so apparently one (or more) of the ingredients in this toothpaste acts as an irritant. Overall, I wouldn't recommend this toothpaste.  In a market where there are so many other varieties to choose from, including from the Colgate brand, there's much better toothpastes to choose from that will provide better overall results without irritating the lips and gums.

reviewTitle: Mild burning sensation, triggers acid reflux
reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States 🇺🇸 on August 31, 2021
reviewDescription: If you have acid reflux, and need to avoid foods that trigger it, this toothpaste is probably not for you.  At first I thought it was a coincidence, but I noticed that right after brushing with Total SF, I experienced acid reflux symptoms.  Further testing revealed that it was the sole cause.  Specifically, any paste containing stannous fluoride instead of sodium fluoride gives me a burning sensation in my mouth and stomach.The other thing to not about this paste is that is causes a slippery film to remain on teeth for hours.  This may nor may not be something you like.Overall, while I do understand the antimicrobial benefits for stannous fluoride, it's rough on my GI tract (even the tiny amount that gets swallowed).  Sticking with sodium fluoride toothpastes for now.

reviewTitle: Lots of dental benefits a plus, the sucralose a big negative
reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States 🇺🇸 on January 18, 2019
reviewDescription: My wife is a longtime dental hygienist who informed me that in her world, Colgate Total is a top-of-the-line toothpaste.That's no surprise, given its many benefits and brand recognition. Within this "Whole Mouth Health" toothpaste are ingredients that fight cavities, plaque, gingivitis, and tarter. The clean-mint white gel also protects enamel, gives sensitive teeth relief, fights bad breath, and whitens teeth. And it doesn't just help teeth - Colgate Total also manages to protect a person's tongue and cheeks.That's all impressive, so why am I giving this toothpaste a mere two stars? Because among its numerous teeth-enhancing ingredients is sucralose, which I'm not a fan of.Yes, I realize people don't swallow their toothpaste, but I imagine anyone could inadvertently swallow trace amounts every day, perhaps without even knowing it. Beyond that, my question is WHY must a toothpaste add sucralose for sweetening purposes? There are other ways to sweeten products.As an example, Colgate's MaxFresh with Whitening toothpaste doesn't contain ingredients that are as pure as the driven snow, but at least it uses saccharin instead of sucralose. Arm & Hammer's Advanced White toothpaste, which may have both Colgate toothpaste brands beat, also does not contain sucralose. To its credit, at least Colgate Total doesn't contain triclosan.In fairness, I can't deny that the scaled-back mint taste of this foamy toothpaste is good and refreshing and not overwhelming, unlike the harsh, overly minty taste of the aforementioned Colgate MaxFresh. Nonetheless, I can't get behind a toothpaste that contains sucralose, especially when there are so many other toothpaste options that don't contain the ingredient.

reviewTitle: Cavity Protection, Good Taste, Stand Up Tube
reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States 🇺🇸 on March 24, 2021
reviewDescription: When considering a toothpaste to purchase/use, there are a couple of things to keep in mind.  One is the active ingredients and the second is taste.  There are two major types of fluoride found in toothpaste.  One is sodium monofluorophosphate, the other is stannous fluoride.  If you are looking for cavity protection, make sure you go with stannous fluoride.The Colgate Total Gum Protection contains stannous fluoride, so it offers cavity protection.  The less expensive varieties contain the sodium fluoride.Taste is always individual.  For me, the Colgate Total has a more refreshing taste than the less expensive sodium fluoride varieties.You will pay slightly more for the Total variety.  But toothpaste is much less expensive than visits to the dentist.One other positive feature is the cap is designed so you can stand the tube upright, saving counter space.This is worth the slightly extra price given the taste, cavity protection and the tube design.

reviewDescription: I'm kind of a snob when it comes to toothpaste.  I love trying unusual foreign, indie and/or all natural brands in unique flavors (like fenugreek, lemongrass, cardamom and wintergreen).  I love the the sophisticated package designs and how they elevate the look of my bathroom vanity.  After several years of almost entirely avoiding the big US brands, like Crest and Colgate, I almost forgot how effective they are at cleaning your teeth and freshening  your breath.  As a veteran of several different jet black charcoal toothpastes that stained my towels and left my sink looking like a gravel pit, I'm thrilled to find this Colgate Total that includes a swirl of charcoal but not enough to make the paste entirely black.  This stuff really has it all - it's great for sensitive teeth, has a bit of grit for effectively cleaning tartar (and giving that pleasant smoothness to the surface of the teeth), it has mild whitening capabilities and, above all, a crisp minty flavor that leaves my mouth feeling ultra-clean and my breath remarkably fresh. As you can see in my picture, the paste is a creamy white color that is streaked with the black charcoal.  It is not made completely of solid black charcoal. It doesn't stain my sink or my towels when I'm finished either.It works up a good foam and spreads far and you only have to use a little bit. reviewDescription: Since hitting middle-age my gums have bled a little more readily than they used to, particularly during teeth cleanings. It has the same active ingredient (0.454% stannous fluoride) and performs very well as an anticaries, antimicrobial and antihypersensitivity toothpaste.  I like the clean flavor, but more important, bleeding gums are no longer an issue.Anyone who googles stannous fluoride may read that it can stain teeth.  I asked my dentist about that, and he said only stronger stannous fluoride products (like prescribed ones) will do that.  I’ve noticed no staining.  I will continue using this product, along with an electric toothbrush and water flosser, as part of my routine oral hygiene.  They have made a big difference in healthier gums.

reviewTitle: If you have paralyzing mouth pain, go to the store and buy this toothpaste right now. Good Health.
reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States 🇺🇸 on November 20, 2019
reviewDescription: Hello,Although I bought this toothpaste at CVS, I was compelled to come write a review. I was suffering from extreme sensitivity which I believe was due to bad oral health caused by an inferior toothpaste. I went on Amazon and bought a fluoride free toothpaste (because I'm not deep state)  and after a couple months I started getting sensitive teeth and paralyzing mouth pain, where it was so bad I had to stop what I was doing, sit down and take a couple ibuprofen. This continued for awhile. If this sounds like you, I encourage you to try this toothpaste.Let me be clear, I do not blame the lack of sodium fluoride, I blame the bacteria that was allowed to grow in my gum line (gingivitis) due to a false sense of clean - the other ingredients were included coconut oil and other hippie dippie stuff. Believe me, I love natural ingredients, but this time it didn't work.I tried some normal Colgate sensitive toothpaste with the Potassium Nitrate, and all the mouth washes and flossing in the world, but nothing worked when that ibuprofen wore off - and it just got worse and worse. Finally I saw a commercial on Hulu for this toothpaste and I read about what this new ingredient Stannous Fluoride was all about. This new ingredient was discovered in the 50s and I guess was a little more expensive than sodium fluoride, and was a little grittier so barely anyone used it. Well now I use it...and I will continue to use it. How can you deny one ingredient that does so much, sensitivity, cavities, kills bacteria and more? I feel very excellent now, only after 2 days. Want to talk about fluoride and mind control? How about when your mouth hurts so bad you can barely move, that is mind control.  I am very aware the triclosan of the past Colgate Total did not disappear when rinsed down the drain and got into our water supply. That is in the past now - welcome to the future. WWG1WGA

reviewTitle: Shockingly bad residue which lasts for hours
reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States on December 4, 2022
reviewDescription: I've used a ton of toothpastes over the years, but this is the only on which merits a negative review.It starts out with a bit of excessive foaming (fine), and a slightly bitter taste (also no big deal).BUT, after you are done brushing and thoroughly rinsing (careful not to swallow any), it leaves a slimy coating on your mouth which lasts hours.  I imagine this is part of how it works to prevent bacteria from adhering to your teeth and gums, but....it leaves a truly bitter taste that you CANNOT get rid, not matter how much rinsing you do.This taste lasts for hours.  The kicker is that it actually impairs your taste buds so much that a meal eaten about 30 minutes after brushing will taste about 25% as strong as it should. Your taste bud are so coated by this stuff that they don't function.The icing om the cake is that this toothpaste is so acidic it triggers acid reflux -- something almost no foods or drinks do to me.So, I am left with a growling stomach, terrible taste throughout my mouth and the inability to enjoy food!  Apparently some people like this stuff, but never again for me.

reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States 🇺🇸 on February 14, 2019
reviewDescription: It’s been a long time since we used Colgate toothpaste. For a year, we have been using various fluoride free toothpastes, some with baking soda and some without. They worked ok tough some were gritty. But I did find that my teeth, especially the gums suffered a little for it. We ended up with a fluoride and baking soda toothpaste we have been using for several months.Recently we thought we would try a different toothpaste and so here we are with Colgate Total whitening gel toothpaste.First thing I noticed on opening the box was the tube. It’s a thin plastic tube that is much easier to squeeze and the cap is not the usual small twist off cap you unscrew and eventually lose somewhere in the bathroom. This tube has a large flip top cap that stays attached to the tube. It takes a moment to close and keeps stray shavings, hair or other bathroom gunk off where the toothpaste comes out.The toothpaste itself is a semi-transparent gel with white pinstripes along the length. I noticed it was easy to spread on the brush and, when brushing your teeth, it has some kind of binding and slight foaming quality that holds the paste loosely together. This toothpaste feels very smooth.The taste is nice, not overbearing and soft mint. It has a subtle hint of something like aniseed. It’s very subtle. My teeth feel smooth and clean and fresh after a brush and my gums didn’t get any irritation over time.With four tubes we will be using this for some time. My husband and I both like it and I expect we will continue using it.  At $4 per tube, the price is reasonable.I recommend it.

reviewDescription: I didn't purchase this from Amazon; I just wanted to provide an honest review. Then about 9 years ago I started using Colgate total clean mint and I'll NEVER stop using this.  This toothpaste is a miracle and a godsend.  Seriously, I haven't had a cavity in like 7 years.  This toothpaste changed my teeth, literally.  The design and the taste of the toothpaste has changed slightly over the years, but I think that's to be expected and the changes are not significant; they are very minor.  Trust me, as someone who at an earlier time/stage in my life had all kinds of teeth issues, let me tell you for a fact that THIS is the toothpaste you want.  I know a lot of people prefer the pronamel toothpaste now adays, but let me tell you if you use this stuff every night you won't Need anything else.  I wouldn't normally be so passionate about toothpaste but this stuff is life changing and that's important because teeth can go south in a hurry.

reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States on February 19, 2019
reviewDescription: This white toothpaste has a minty flavor and does a good job of cleaning the teeth and tongue and leaving the mouth feeling fresh.It contains stannous fluoride instead of the more common sodium fluoride to fight the bacteria that cause plaque and gingivitis and to decrease tooth sensitivity by blocking the dentinal tubules with regular use over time.  I really appreciate being able to get stannous fluoride in a normal toothpaste like this rather than having to buy much more expensive specialty gels, rinses, or pastes.The directions are to use at least a one inch strip of toothpaste to brush for at least one minute twice a day.  However, I don't use that much because my dentist recommends swishing the toothpaste in the mouth for several minutes after brushing and then spitting it out but not rinsing or drinking for fifteen minutes, basically using it as a fluoride mouthwash.  Unlike sodium fluoride, stannous fluoride can discolor the teeth but I have never noticed that with any toothpaste and if there were staining, it would not be permanent and would be removed with normal prophylaxis.The 4.8 oz. or 36 g tubes have convenient flip caps.

reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States on January 19, 2019
reviewDescription: When I first learned to brush my teeth Colgate was the brand that my family used. There were far fewer choices back then and a lot less marketing hyperbole about special magical powers that one brand has over another.  Toothpaste is one of those things that some have a strong brand preference for and never switch to anything else.  Me, I buy whatever is on sale or whatever looks interesting at the time, including unique and exotic toothpastes from all over the world.  But I have to say, Colgate is a brand that I always trust.This product doesn’t seem to be any different than what has been available for a long time, the word “new” appears to indicate that there is a change in the usage and warning label.  It does the job it’s supposed to, it tastes good, and at about three bucks a tube is on a par with most other brands.I don’t believe it has any magical whitening powers though, that ability requires a specialty product, not an everyday toothpaste. And as far as the rest of the chemicals in the ingredient list I’m not qualified to say if they are good or bad, and I would highly suspect anyone who claims the opposite unless they are a chemist or scientist.  And even then, an ingredient that may be beneficial to one person may be harmful to another so my advice is that if you aren’t sure, consult your dental professional instead of reading reviews from people you don’t know.For being trustworthy, budget friendly and having no obvious negatives I like this product.

reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States on March 14, 2021
reviewDescription: I am seriously impressed by the changes I've noticed since I started using this toothpaste.I kind of drew the genetic short straw and inherited a predisposition toward periodontal disease. Despite regular cleanings, brushing three times a day, flossing at least twice, mouthwash and daily water flosser use, my gums are in terrible shape. My dentist actually recommended I find a toothpaste with a focus on gum health, specifically.So I was eager to give this a try. I'll be honest. First impression wasn't great. I prefer gel over paste because I don't like the texture of toothpaste. And the flavor isn't good. Not very minty at all. But! I was determined to stick with it anyway.And I'm so glad I did! After about a week of daily use, I noticed that my gums were far less inflamed. They don't bleed when I floss at all anymore. And my breath was noticeably less morning breath-y.So whatever this product is supposed to do is absolutely working for me. I'm so happy with this change!I've gotten used to the taste and texture now, so it doesn't bother me. Totally worth it, regardless.If you've got gum issues, definitely give this a try. Highly recommend!

reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States on March 10, 2021
reviewDescription: According to the description of this Colgate Total Gum Protection Toothpaste with Stannous Fluoride and Zinc product page the formulation includes mint.  The mint information is not listed on the box or the tubes.  I can detect a small amount of mint flavor and I'm sort of okay with that but I definitely prefer not to have my toothpaste flavored with anything.  My dentist and I agree that I do best when I use a toothpaste with a fairly high abrasive ingredient to help keep down tartar build-up between cleaning appointments.  I normally use a Crest toothpaste that has that higher amount of abrasive ingredient, this Colgate doesn't feel like it meets that level of cleaning for me but I will continue to use this to give it a fair trial.The 12 hour antibacterial protection vs non-bacterial protection is reached when you brush twice daily for 4 weeks.  I do like that this toothpaste targets all parts of my mouth.  I was surprised to see on the box and tube that the recommendation is to brush *at least* one minute twice per day.  That doesn't seem long enough to me for a recommendation for product use.

reviewTitle: Good mainstream toothpaste for sensitivity; does contain stannous fluoride which can yellow teeth
reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States on March 9, 2021
reviewDescription: Colgate Total Gum Protection Toothpaste with Stannous Fluoride and Zinc, Sensitivity Relief and Cavity Protection Mint, 9.6 Ounce (Pack of 2)I picked out this toothpaste to help with sore gums/irritated gums and sensitive teeth, and it has helped! It’s in a large tube and has a good minty flavor. Easy to brush with and use. I tend to have soreness in specific areas of my mouth and have noticed a decrease, although it hasn’t been perfect; I had a little soreness one day that did not go away until I took an anti-inflammatory. Not sure if this was caused by tooth pain; could have been related to the ear, to be fair.One thing to note – this product uses Stannous Fluoride, which is typically used in sensitivity toothpastes, but can cause teeth to yellow a little. Colgate mentions that the product is formulated to help prevent this but it’s something to keep in mind. I have been using this toothpaste for about a week and have not noticed any yellowing in my teeth.Overall, this is a good toothpaste for sensitivity. I’d recommend it.

reviewTitle: Check the expiration date to see if it works for your life.
reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States on April 3, 2020
reviewDescription: Great toothpaste as it does not irritate my mouth like others do. Very smooth feeling, and subtle flavor. However, note the expiration date when you first receive your package. Luckily, I did not get any expired products like other reviewers have but I say this because I am the only person in my household that uses this toothpaste and buying in bulk comes with certain issues. The first time I purchased this in late December 2019, the pack would not have expired until January 2021 leaving me with plenty of time and more to finish the 4-pack. I repurchased in April 2020 because I had given away 2 tubes to people who ran out and they could not buy it in stores due to the coronavirus hoarders. This time, my new order would expire in October 2020 giving me 5 months to use before I’d have to throw it out on October 1st (I don’t want to use it in October, if it says it expires then). With a Sonicare toothbrush, I don’t need to use globs and globs to get the job done. I barely finished my 2nd tube (Today is April 3, 2020) that I opened in February as it takes me about 1.5-2 months to finish one tube. I will probably not be able to finish using the entire 4-pack by September, so I guess I’ll be giving away more toothpaste. Besides this tiny issue, I really like this toothpaste and will continue ordering and just be mindful of the expiration dates.

My gums feel healthier and I know that the fluoride is beneficial. The whitening aspect is secondary, but it seems to do as good of a job as other popular toothpastes in that respect. I've used "white strips" or similar products occasionally if I want to whiten my teeth. I feel that regular brushing and care is as effective as anything, unless you smoke, or drink highly staining things all day long. Thankfully, I don't.I am very pleased with this toothpaste and plan to continue using it rather than our old brand. reviewTitle: Has been working for my sensitive teeth without any unpleasant taste
reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States 🇺🇸 on February 3, 2019
reviewDescription: I've been using Sensodyne (usually ProNamel) for several years to help with sensitivity around my gum lines, especially with acidic foods and drinks like lemonade.  This Colgate uses stannous fluoride for both cavity fighting and sensitivity, and not being familiar with it, I was skeptical that it would work as well.  So far, I actually think that it does.After using this, I did some research on stannous fluoride and learned that it's been around for a long time.  Like sodium fluoride, it fights cavities, but it also is antimicrobial unlike sodium fluoride.  Making it (at least used to) include tin, which would make it taste metallic and gritty, and also stain teeth.  Newer formulations prevent or mostly prevent all of those.To me, this doesn't taste much different than any other mint toothpaste.  No metallic taste, no grit, nothing out of the ordinary.  I also haven't noticed any staining from it.What I have noticed is that my teeth aren't sensitive, which is how they always were with Sensodyne.  Given that this Colgate is a lot less expensive, I'm definitely going to be considering this heavily the next time that I go shopping.

reviewTitle: Another Toothpaste, For Better or Worse
reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States on February 14, 2019
reviewDescription: When it comes to toothpaste, I am quite promiscuous:  I tend to buy whatever is on sale, or whatever represents the best value.  Since the Chinese toothpaste scare several years ago, I prefer my toothpaste to be made in U.S.A., Canada, or western Europe, and, according to the Colgate company's website, the Colgate Total line is made in Morristown, Tennessee, USA.  In addition, I tend to like a less sweet, slightly minty toothpaste as opposed to a sweet and/or fruity toothpaste flavor.This newly-introduced Colgate Total is a revision of an earlier formula, which, according to the manufacturer, provides a superior level of cleaning compared to the old formula.  Since I am not brand-loyal to toothpaste, I honestly cannot tell you whether or not this "new and improved" toothpaste is, indeed, "new and improved."  I can only speak to my recent experience with the revised Total formula.This iteration of Colgate Total did not have a particularly overpowering mint flavor; more a hint of mint than a mouthful of mint; to me, this was a great thing.  The sweetness of the toothpaste earned my lady's praise, though I prefer less sweetness (if any) in my toothpaste.  While I realized the sweetness did not come from sugar, I have always felt strange cleaning my teeth with something sugary sweet - like I am defeating the purpose of brushing.  The toothpaste lathered slightly, a telltale sign of the presence of SLS (sodium lauryl sulfate), an ingredient I do not miss when using a natural toothpaste brand like Tom's of Maine or Jason (I don't buy the pseudo-science around SLS or any other ingredient, I simply prefer a less lathery toothpaste in my mouth).  After brushing, my teeth seemed both smooth and clean, as they did with Crest, Tom's of Maine, Parodontax, Jason, and all the other ADA-approved toothpastes I've used over the years.On balance, I will use Colgate Total until I am through all four tubes, but I do not plan to buy it specifically, unless it proves to be the best value when I am ready to purchase more toothpaste.

reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States 🇺🇸 on February 14, 2019
reviewDescription: I find that this Colgate Total Whole Mouth Health works great at cleaning not only my teeth but my whole mouth feels cleaner. It is not just the minty flavor as I find that it does not have as much mintiness as the brand I was using before trying this Colgate and to be honest, it is much more pleasant. Kind of a soft minty flavor that does not bite. I noticed this when I first used this toothpaste..a very pleasant surprise. I find I am not in as much of a hurry to get the toothpaste out of my mouth..so I am brushing a bit longer.I also like that this is a total toothpaste that supposedly takes care of your whole mouth..cavities, plaque, gingivitis, enamel, tartar, breath, whitens and even has sensitivity relief. reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States 🇺🇸 on January 18, 2019
reviewDescription: This toothpaste is unique compared to most in that it uses stannous fluoride instead of sodium fluoride.  The benefit is that stannous fluoride has antibacterial properties in addition to tooth decay prevention - better treatment of tartar, gingivitis, tooth sensitivity, and decay.  It's been around a long time but hasn't been as common because in its early days it was more expensive, didn't taste as good, and could stain teeth.  In recent years new production processes have addressed the staining and taste issues.  It's now found in Crest's more expensive Advanced Pro toothpastes and Colgate items like this one.  It tastes good - very similar to others - with a fresh minty flavor, and is pleasant to use.  Great toothpaste!

reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States 🇺🇸 on December 13, 2018
reviewDescription: Still has the only patented ingredient scientifically proven to fight gum disease. Reason alone to buy this, even though it costs a bit more. Ask your dentist! We have three different family dentists and each one recommends only Total.The whitening stuff, eh, who cares. If it works, it works, if not, and I end up with teeth that look like normal human teeth rather than slabs of polished ivory, I am fine with it. I find it regrettable that Colgate puts this claim in at all, but the zeitgeist at present is for abnormally white teeth, so if they have to put that claim in to sell another 5.7% more of the product, I won't blame them.Gel is easier to use with power toothbrushes than the paste.All in all, a great and unique product in the realm of dental care. Maybe one day the patent will end and the formula will show up in other brands. Till then, Total for us.
